[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] C++ was designed with systems programming and embedded, resource-constrained software and large systems in mind, with performance, efficiency, and flexibility of use as its design highlights.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] C++ is standardized by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), with the latest standard version ratified and published by ISO in October 2024 as *ISO/IEC 14882:2024* (informally known as C++23).
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] The C++ programming language was initially standardized in 1998 as *ISO/IEC 14882:1998*, which was then amended by the C++03, C++11, C++14, C++17, and C++20 standards.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] The next C++23 standard superseded these with new features and an enlarged standard library.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] Before the initial standardization in 1998, C++ was developed by Stroustrup at Bell Labs since 1979 as an extension of the C language; he wanted an efficient and flexible language similar to C that also provided high-level features for program organization.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] Since 2012, C++ has been on a three-year release schedule with C++29 as the next planned standard.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] In 1979, Bjarne Stroustrup, a Danish computer scientist, began work on "C with Classes", the predecessor to C++.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] The motivation for creating a new language originated from Stroustrup's experience in programming for his PhD thesis.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup found that Simula had features that were very helpful for large software development, but the language was too slow for practical use, while BCPL was fast but too low-level to be suitable for large software development.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] When Stroustrup started working in AT&T Bell Labs, he had the problem of analyzing the UNIX kernel with respect to distributed computing.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] Remembering his PhD experience, Stroustrup set out to enhance the C language with Simula-like features.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] C was chosen because it was general-purpose, fast, portable, and widely used.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] In addition to C and Simula's influences, other languages influenced this new language, including ALGOL 68, Ada, CLU, and ML.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] Initially, Stroustrup's "C with Classes" added features to the C compiler, Cpre, including classes, derived classes, strong typing, inlining, and default arguments.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] In 1982, Stroustrup began designing a cleaned-up and extended successor to C with Classes, using traditional compiler technology.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] The language was briefly called C84 before the name C++ was adopted; the name was suggested by Rick Mascitti and refers to C's `++` increment operator.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] The resulting language included virtual functions, function and operator overloading, references, `const`, improved type checking, user-controlled free-store memory allocation (`new`/`delete`), and BCPL-style single-line `//` comments.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup also designed and implemented Cfront, the C++ compiler front end, between spring 1982 and summer 1983.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] In 1984, Stroustrup implemented the first stream input/output library.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] The idea of providing an output operator rather than a named output function was suggested by Doug McIlroy (who had previously suggested Unix pipes).
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] In 1985, the first edition of *The C++ Programming Language* was released, which became the definitive reference for the language, as there was not yet an official standard.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] The first commercial implementation of C++ was released in October of the same year.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] In 1989, C++ 2.0 was released, followed by the updated second edition of *The C++ Programming Language* in 1991.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] New features in 2.0 included multiple inheritance, abstract classes, static member functions, const member functions, and protected members.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] In 1990, *The Annotated C++ Reference Manual* was published.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] This work became the basis for the future standard.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] Later feature additions included templates, exceptions, namespaces, new casts, and a Boolean type.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] In 1998, C++98 was released, standardizing the language, and a minor update (C++03) was released in 2003.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] After C++98, C++ evolved relatively slowly until, in 2011, the C++11 standard was released, adding numerous new features, enlarging the standard library further, and providing more facilities to C++ programmers.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] After a minor C++14 update released in December 2014, various new additions were introduced in C++17.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] After becoming finalized in February 2020, a draft of the C++20 standard was approved on 4 September 2020, and officially published on 15 December 2020.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] On January 3, 2018, Stroustrup was announced as the 2018 winner of the Charles Stark Draper Prize for Engineering, "for conceptualizing and developing the C++ programming language".
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] In December 2022, C++ ranked third on the TIOBE index, surpassing Java for the first time in the history of the index.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] As of November 2024, the language ranks second after Python, with Java being in third.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] In March 2025, Stroustrup issued a call for the language community to defend it.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] Since the language allows manual memory management, bugs that represent security risks such as buffer overflow may be introduced in programs when inadvertently misused by the programmer.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] According to Stroustrup, "the name signifies the evolutionary nature of the changes from C." This name is credited to Rick Mascitti (mid-1983) and was first used in December 1983.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] When Mascitti was questioned informally in 1992 about the naming, he indicated that it was given in a tongue-in-cheek spirit.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] The name comes from C's `++` operator (which increments the value of a variable) and a common naming convention of using "+" to indicate an enhanced computer program.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] During C++'s development period, the language had been referred to as "new C" and "C with Classes" before acquiring its final name.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] C++ is standardized by an ISO working group known as JTC1/SC22/WG21.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] The working group holds three week-long meetings each year.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] So far, it has published seven revisions of the C++ standard and is currently working on the next revision, C++26.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] In 1998, the ISO working group standardized C++ for the first time as *ISO/IEC 14882:1998*, which is informally known as *C++98*.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] In 2003, it published a new version of the C++ standard called *ISO/IEC 14882:2003*, which fixed problems identified in C++98.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] The next major revision of the standard was informally referred to as "C++0x", but it was not released until 2011.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] C++11 (14882:2011) included many additions to both the core language and the standard library.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] In 2014, C++14 (also known as C++1y) was released as a small extension to C++11, featuring mainly bug fixes and small improvements.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] The Draft International Standard ballot procedures completed in mid-August 2014.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] After C++14, a major revision C++17, informally known as C++1z, was completed by the ISO C++ committee in mid July 2017 and was approved and published in December 2017.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] More technical specifications are in development and pending approval.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] The C++ language has two main components: a direct mapping of hardware features provided primarily by the C subset, and zero-overhead abstractions based on those mappings.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup describes C++ as "a light-weight abstraction programming language [designed] for building and using efficient and elegant abstractions"; and "offering both hardware access and abstraction is the basis of C++.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] A hello world program that conforms to the C standard is also a valid C++ hello world program.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] The C++ standard specifies both the core language and the standard library.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] The library clauses describe the contents of the library, how a well-formed C++ program uses it, and the requirements placed on conforming implementations.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] The standard library is organized into areas such as language support, diagnostics, memory management, metaprogramming, general utilities, containers, iterators, ranges, algorithms, strings, text processing, numerics, time, input/output, and concurrency support.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] It also provides the facilities of the C standard library through C++ headers such as `<cstdio>` and `<cstdlib>`; except for names defined as macros in C, these declarations are placed in namespace `std`.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] Library facilities are traditionally made available by including standard headers, for example `#include <vector>`.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] Since C++20, importable standard library headers may also be imported as header units.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] C++23 added the named standard library modules `std` and `std.compat`: `std` exports declarations in namespace `std`, while `std.compat` also exports corresponding global namespace declarations for C library facilities.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] A major influence on the standard library was the Standard Template Library (STL), a generic programming library proposed to the C++ standards committee by Alexander Stepanov and Meng Lee in 1994.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] Its model of containers, iterators, and generic algorithms became part of the Standard C++ Library, although the standard library also includes many other facilities, such as input/output, localization, diagnostics, and the C library subset.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] The main aim is to efficiently and consistently write type and resource safe C++.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] Despite this, the guidelines are not endorsed by the ISO C++ standards committee and do not represent the consensus of the committee.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] The Core Guidelines were announced in the opening keynote at CPPCon 2015.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] The Guidelines are accompanied by the Guideline Support Library (GSL), a header-only library of types and functions to implement the Core Guidelines and static checker tools for enforcing Guideline rules.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] One of the largest implementations of this is Microsoft's implementation.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] Many of the existing features in the GSL have been later integrated into the language, such as `std::byte`, smart pointers, and `std::span`.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] To give compiler vendors greater freedom, the C++ standards committee decided not to dictate the implementation of name mangling, exception handling, and other implementation-specific features.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] The downside of this decision is that object code produced by different compilers is expected to be incompatible.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] There are, however, attempts to standardize compilers for particular machines or operating systems.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] For example, the Itanium C++ ABI is processor-independent (despite its name) and is implemented by GCC and Clang.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] C++ is often considered to be a superset of C but this is not strictly true.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] Most C code can easily be made to compile correctly in C++ but there are a few differences that cause some valid C code to be invalid or behave differently in C++.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] For example, C allows implicit conversion from `void*` to other pointer types but C++ does not (for type safety reasons).
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] Also, C++ defines many new keywords, such as `new` and `class`, which may be used as identifiers (for example, variable names) in a C program.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] Some incompatibilities have been removed by the 1999 revision of the C standard (C99), which now supports C++ features such as line comments (`//`) and declarations mixed with code.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] Some of the C99-introduced features were included in the subsequent version of the C++ standard, C++11 (out of those which were not redundant).
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] However, the C++11 standard introduces new incompatibilities, such as disallowing assignment of a string literal to a character pointer, which remains valid C.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] To intermix C and C++ code, any function declaration or definition that is to be called from/used both in C and C++ must be declared with C linkage by placing it within an `extern "C" {/*...*/}` block.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] Such a function may not rely on features depending on name mangling (i.e., function overloading).
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] Programs developed in C or C++ often utilize inline assembly to take advantage of its low-level functionalities, greater speed, and enhanced control compared to high-level programming languages when optimizing for performance is essential.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] C++ provides support for embedding assembly language using asm declarations, but the compatibility of inline assembly varies significantly between compilers and architectures.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] Unlike high-level language features such as Python or Java, assembly code is highly dependent on the underlying processor and compiler implementation.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] Different C++ compilers implement inline assembly in distinct ways.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] C++ provides two primary methods of integrating ASM code: standalone assembly files, where assembly code is written separately and linked with C++ code.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/c] And inline assembly, where assembly code is embedded within C++ code using compiler-specific extensions.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] In software engineering, **code coverage**, also called **test coverage**, is a percentage measure of the degree to which the source code of a program is executed when a particular test suite is run.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] A program with high code coverage has more of its source code executed during testing, which suggests it has a lower chance of containing undetected software bugs compared to a program with low code coverage.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] Many different metrics can be used to calculate test coverage.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] Some of the most basic are the percentage of program subroutines and the percentage of program statements called during execution of the test suite.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] Code coverage was among the first methods invented for systematic software testing.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] The first published reference was by Miller and Maloney in *Communications of the ACM*, in 1963.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] To measure what percentage of code has been executed by a test suite, one or more *coverage criteria* are used.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] These are usually defined as rules or requirements, which a test suite must satisfy.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] Assume this function is a part of some bigger program and this program was run with some test suite.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] In programming languages that do not perform short-circuit evaluation, condition coverage does not necessarily imply branch coverage.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] However, this set of tests does not satisfy branch coverage since neither case will meet the `if` condition.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] Fault injection may be necessary to ensure that all conditions and branches of exception-handling code have adequate coverage during testing.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] A combination of function coverage and branch coverage is sometimes also called **decision coverage**.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] This criterion requires that every point of entry and exit in the program has been invoked at least once, and every decision in the program has taken on all possible outcomes at least once.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] In this context, the decision is a Boolean expression comprising conditions and zero or more Boolean operators.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] This definition is not the same as branch coverage, however, the term *decision coverage* is sometimes used as a synonym for it.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] However, the above tests set will not satisfy modified condition/decision coverage, since in the first test, the value of 'b' and in the second test the value of 'c' would not influence the output.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] This criterion requires that all combinations of conditions inside each decision are tested.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] Safety-critical or dependable applications are often required to demonstrate 100% of some form of test coverage.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] For example, the ECSS-E-ST-40C standard demands 100% statement and decision coverage for two out of four different criticality levels; for the other ones, target coverage values are up to negotiation between supplier and customer.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] Some of the coverage criteria above are connected.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] For instance, path coverage implies decision, statement and entry/exit coverage.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] Decision coverage implies statement coverage, because every statement is part of a branch.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] Full path coverage, of the type described above, is usually impractical or impossible.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] Any module with a succession of n decisions in it can have up to $2^{n}$ paths within it; loop constructs can result in an infinite number of paths.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] Many paths may also be infeasible, in that there is no input to the program under test that can cause that particular path to be executed.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] However, a general-purpose algorithm for identifying infeasible paths has been proven to be impossible (such an algorithm could be used to solve the halting problem).
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] Basis path testing is for instance a method of achieving complete branch coverage without achieving complete path coverage.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] Methods for practical path coverage testing instead attempt to identify classes of code paths that differ only in the number of loop executions, and to achieve "basis path" coverage the tester must cover all the path classes.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] The target software is built with special options or libraries and run under a controlled environment, to map every executed function to the function points in the source code.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] This allows testing parts of the target software that are rarely or never accessed under normal conditions, and helps reassure that the most important conditions (function points) have been tested.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] The resulting output is then analyzed to see what areas of code have not been exercised and the tests are updated to include these areas as necessary.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] Combined with other test coverage methods, the aim is to develop a rigorous, yet manageable, set of regression tests.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] Software authors can look at test coverage results to devise additional tests and input or configuration sets to increase the coverage over vital functions.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] Two common forms of test coverage are statement (or line) coverage and branch (or edge) coverage.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] Line coverage reports on the execution footprint of testing in terms of which lines of code were executed to complete the test.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] Edge coverage reports which branches or code decision points were executed to complete the test.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] They both report a coverage metric, measured as a percentage.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] The meaning of this depends on what form(s) of coverage have been used, as 67% branch coverage is more comprehensive than 67% statement coverage.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] Generally, test coverage tools incur computation and logging in addition to the actual program thereby slowing down the application, so typically this analysis is not done in production.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] As one might expect, there are classes of software that cannot be feasibly subjected to these coverage tests, though a degree of coverage mapping can be approximated through analysis rather than direct testing.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] There are also some sorts of defects which are affected by such tools.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] In particular, some race conditions or similar real time sensitive operations can be masked when run under test environments; though conversely, some of these defects may become easier to find as a result of the additional overhead of the testing code.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] Most professional software developers use C1 and C2 coverage.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] C1 stands for statement coverage and C2 for branch or condition coverage.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] With a combination of C1 and C2, it is possible to cover most statements in a code base.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] Statement coverage would also cover function coverage with entry and exit, loop, path, state flow, control flow and data flow coverage.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] With these methods, it is possible to achieve nearly 100% code coverage in most software projects.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] Test coverage is one consideration in the safety certification of avionics equipment.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] The guidelines by which avionics gear is certified by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) is documented in DO-178B and DO-178C.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/code-coverage] Test coverage is also a requirement in part 6 of the automotive safety standard ISO 26262 *Road Vehicles - Functional Safety*.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] In computer programming, a **mock object** is an object that imitates a production object in limited ways.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] A programmer might use a mock object as a test double for software testing.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] A mock object can also be used in generic programming.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] A mock object can be useful to the software tester like a car designer uses a crash test dummy to simulate a human in a vehicle impact.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] In a unit test, mock objects can simulate the behavior of complex, real objects and are therefore useful when a real object is impractical or impossible to incorporate into a unit test.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] For example, an alarm clock program which causes a bell to ring at a certain time might get the current time from a time service.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] To test this, the test must wait until the alarm time to know whether it has rung the bell correctly.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] If a mock time service is used in place of the real time service, it can be programmed to provide the bell-ringing time (or any other time) regardless of the real time, so that the alarm clock program can be tested in isolation.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] Mock objects have the same interface as the real objects they mimic, allowing a client object to remain unaware of whether it is using a real object or a mock object.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] Many available mock object frameworks allow the programmer to specify which methods will be invoked on a mock object, in what order, what parameters will be passed to them, and what values will be returned.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] Thus, the behavior of a complex object such as a network socket can be mimicked by a mock object, allowing the programmer to discover whether the object being tested responds appropriately to the wide variety of states such mock objects may be in.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] The definitions of mock, fake and stub are not consistent across the literature.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] Nonetheless, all represent a production object in a testing environment by exposing the same interface.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] Regardless of name, the simplest form returns pre-arranged responses (as in a method stub) and the most complex form imitates a production object's complete logic.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] Such a test object might contain assertions to examine the context of each call.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] For example, a mock object might assert the order in which its methods are called, or assert consistency of data across method calls.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] In the book *The Art of Unit Testing* mocks are described as a fake object that helps decide whether a test failed or passed by verifying whether an interaction with an object occurred.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] In that book, *fakes* are anything that is not real, which, based on their usage, can be either *stubs* or *mocks*.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] Consider an example where an authorization subsystem has been mocked.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] The mock object implements an `isUserAllowed(task : Task) : boolean` method to match that in the real authorization class.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] Many advantages follow if it also exposes an `isAllowed : boolean` property, which is not present in the real class.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] This allows test code to easily set the expectation that a user will, or will not, be granted permission in the next call and therefore to readily test the behavior of the rest of the system in either case.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] Similarly, mock-only settings could ensure that subsequent calls to the sub-system will cause it to throw an exception, hang without responding, or return `null` etc.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] Thus, it is possible to develop and test client behaviors for realistic fault conditions in back-end sub-systems, as well as for their expected responses.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] Without such a simple and flexible mock system, testing each of these situations may be too laborious for them to be given proper consideration.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] A mock database object's `save(person : Person)` method may not contain much (if any) implementation code.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] It might check the existence and perhaps the validity of the Person object passed in for saving (see fake vs. mock discussion above), but beyond that there might be no other implementation.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] The mock method could add an entry to a public log string.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] The entry need be no more than "Person saved", or it may include some details from the person object instance, such as a name or ID.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] If the test code also checks the final contents of the log string after various series of operations involving the mock database, then it is possible to verify that in each case exactly the expected number of database saves have been performed.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] This can find otherwise invisible performance-sapping bugs, for example, where a developer, nervous of losing data, has coded repeated calls to `save()` where just one would have sufficed.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] Programmers working with the test-driven development (TDD) method make use of mock objects when writing software.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] Mock objects meet the interface requirements of, and stand in for, more complex real ones; thus they allow programmers to write and unit-test functionality in one area without calling complex underlying or collaborating classes.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] Using mock objects allows developers to focus their tests on the behavior of the system under test without worrying about its dependencies.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] For example, testing a complex algorithm based on multiple objects being in particular states can be clearly expressed using mock objects in place of real objects.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] Apart from complexity issues and the benefits gained from this separation of concerns, there are practical speed issues involved.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] Developing a realistic piece of software using TDD may easily involve several hundred unit tests.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] If many of these induce communication with databases, web services and other out-of-process or networked systems, then the suite of unit tests will quickly become too slow to be run regularly.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] This in turn leads to bad habits and a reluctance by the developer to maintain the basic tenets of TDD.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] When mock objects are replaced by real ones, the end-to-end functionality will need further testing.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] These will be integration tests rather than unit tests.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] The use of mock objects can closely couple the unit tests to the implementation of the code that is being tested.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] This illustrates that unit tests should test a method's external behavior rather than its internal implementation.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] Over-use of mock objects as part of a suite of unit tests can result in a dramatic increase in the amount of maintenance that needs to be performed on the tests themselves during system evolution as refactoring takes place.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] The improper maintenance of such tests during evolution could allow bugs to be missed that would otherwise be caught by unit tests that use instances of real classes.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] Conversely, simply mocking one method might require far less configuration than setting up an entire real class and therefore reduce maintenance needs.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] Mock objects have to accurately model the behavior of the object they are mocking, which can be difficult to achieve if the object being mocked comes from another developer or project or if it has not even been written yet.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/mock-object] If the behavior is not modelled correctly, then the unit tests may register a pass even though a failure would occur at run time under the same conditions that the unit test is exercising, thus rendering the unit test inaccurate.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] Changes that may require regression testing include bug fixes, software enhancements, configuration changes, and even substitution of electronic components (hardware).
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] As regression test suites tend to grow with each found defect, test automation is frequently involved.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] Sometimes a change impact analysis is performed to determine an appropriate subset of tests (*non-regression analysis*).
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] As software is updated or changed, or reused on a modified target, emergence of new faults and/or re-emergence of old faults is quite common.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] Sometimes re-emergence occurs because a fix gets lost through poor revision control practices (or simple human error in revision control).
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] Often, a fix for a problem will be "fragile" in that it fixes the problem in the narrow case where it was first observed but not in more general cases which may arise over the lifetime of the software.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] Frequently, a fix for a problem in one area inadvertently causes a software bug in another area.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] It may happen that when a feature is redesigned some of the same mistakes that were made in the original implementation of the feature also occur in the redesign.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] In most software development situations, it is considered good coding practice, when a bug is located and fixed, to record a test that exposes the bug and re-run that test regularly after subsequent changes to the program.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] Although this may be done through manual testing procedures using programming techniques, it is often done using automated testing tools.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] Common strategies are to run such a system after every successful compile (for small projects), every night, or once a week.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] Those strategies can be automated by an external tool.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] Regression testing is an integral part of the extreme programming software development method.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] In this method, design documents are replaced by extensive, repeatable, and automated testing of the entire software package throughout each stage of the software development process.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] Regression testing is done after functional testing has concluded, to verify that the other functionalities are working.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] In the corporate world, regression testing has traditionally been performed by a software quality assurance team after the development team has completed work.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] However, defects found at this stage are the most costly to fix.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] This problem is being addressed by the rise of unit testing.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] Although developers have always written test cases as part of the development cycle, these test cases have generally been either functional tests or unit tests that verify only intended outcomes.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] Developer testing compels a developer to focus on unit testing and to include both positive and negative test cases.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] This technique checks all the test cases on the current program to check its integrity.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] Though it is expensive as it needs to re-run all the test cases, it ensures that there are no errors because of the modified code.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] Unlike Retest all, this technique runs a part of the test suite (owing to the cost of retest all) if the cost of selecting the part of the test suite is less than the Retest all technique.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] Prioritize the test cases so as to increase a test suite's rate of fault detection.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] Test case prioritization techniques schedule test cases so that the test cases that are higher in priority are executed before the test cases that have a lower priority.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] This technique is a hybrid of regression test selection and test case prioritization.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] Regression testing is performed when changes are made to the existing functionality of the software or if there is a bug fix in the software.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] Regression testing can be achieved through multiple approaches; if a *test all* approach is followed, it provides certainty that the changes made to the software have not affected the existing functionalities, which are unaltered.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] In agile software development—where the software development life cycles are very short, resources are scarce, and changes to the software are very frequent—regression testing might introduce a lot of unnecessary overhead.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] Regression testing can be used not only for testing the *correctness* of a program but often also for tracking the quality of its output.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] For instance, in the design of a compiler, regression testing could track the code size and the time it takes to compile and execute the test suite cases.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] — Fred Brooks, *The Mythical Man Month*, p.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] Regression tests can be done at any level, from unit through to system integration.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] Functional tests exercise the complete program with various inputs.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] These tests are often automated due to the need for repetition, and may be done by test tools that are not part of the compiler suite.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] Non-functional tests assess aspects such as performance, security, or reliability.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] Conducting non-functional regression tests presents additional challenges.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/regression-testing] For example, detecting changes in performance is often statistically complex, while security issues typically arise from vulnerabilities in the software ecosystem rather than from individual code changes.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Software testing can provide objective, independent information about the quality of software and the risk of its failure to a user or sponsor or any other stakeholder.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Software testing can determine the correctness of software for specific scenarios but cannot determine correctness for all scenarios.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Based on the criteria for measuring correctness from an oracle, software testing employs principles and mechanisms that might recognize a problem.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Examples of oracles include specifications, contracts, comparable products, past versions of the same product, inferences about intended or expected purpose, user or customer expectations, relevant standards, and applicable laws.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Software testing can be functional or non-functional in nature.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Software testing is often dynamic in nature: running the software to verify actual output matches expected.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] It can also be static in nature: reviewing code and its associated documentation.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Software testing is often used to answer the question: Does the software do what it is supposed to do and what it needs to do?
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Information learned from software testing may be used to improve the process by which software is developed.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] A commonly suggested approach to automated testing is the "test pyramid," wherein most of the tests are unit tests, followed by a smaller set of integration tests and finally a few end-to-end (e2e) tests.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] A study conducted by NIST in 2002 reported that software bugs cost the U.S. economy $59.5 billion annually.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] More than a third of this cost could be avoided if better software testing was performed.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Outsourcing software testing because of costs is very common, with China, the Philippines, India and Pakistan being preferred destinations.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Myers initially introduced the separation of debugging from testing in 1979.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Although his attention was on breakage testing ("A successful test case is one that detects an as-yet undiscovered error."), it illustrated the desire of the software engineering community to separate fundamental development activities, such as debugging, from that of verification.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Software testing typically includes handling software bugs – a defect in the code that causes an undesirable result.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Bugs generally slow testing progress and involve programmer assistance to debug and fix.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] For example, a defect in dead code will not be considered a failure.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] A defect that does not cause failure at one point in time may lead to failure later due to environmental changes.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Examples of environment change include running on new computer hardware, changes in data, and interacting with different software.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Software testing is typically goal driven.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] A single defect may result in multiple failure symptoms.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Software testing may involve a Requirements gap – omission from the design for a requirement.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Requirement gaps can often be non-functional requirements such as testability, scalability, maintainability, performance, and security.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] A fundamental limitation of software testing is that testing under *all* combinations of inputs and preconditions (initial state) is not feasible, even with a simple product.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Defects that manifest in unusual conditions are difficult to find in testing.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Also, non-functional dimensions of quality (how it is supposed to *be* versus what it is supposed to *do*) – usability, scalability, performance, compatibility, and reliability – can be subjective; something that constitutes sufficient value to one person may not to another.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Although testing for every possible input is not feasible, testing can use combinatorics to maximize coverage while minimizing tests.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Test automation is the use of software (separate from the software being tested) for controlling the execution of tests and comparing actual outcome with predicted.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Test automation supports testing the system under test (SUT) without manual interaction which can lead to faster test execution and testing more often.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Test automation is a key aspect of continuous testing and often for continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD).
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Software testing can be categorized into levels based on how much of the software system is the focus of a test.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Unit testing, a.k.a. component or module testing, is a form of software testing by which isolated source code is tested to validate expected behavior.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Integration testing is a form of software testing in which multiple software components, modules, or services are tested together to verify they work as expected when combined.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] The focus is on testing the interactions and data exchange between integrated parts, rather than testing components in isolation.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] System testing, a.k.a. end-to-end (E2E) testing, is testing conducted on a complete software system.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] There are many approaches to software testing.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Reviews, walkthroughs, or inspections are referred to as static testing, whereas executing programmed code with a given set of test cases is referred to as dynamic testing.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Static testing is often implicit, like proofreading, plus when programming tools/text editors check source code structure or compilers (precompilers) check syntax and data flow as static program analysis.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Dynamic testing takes place when the program itself is run.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Dynamic testing may begin before the program is 100% complete in order to test particular sections of code and are applied to discrete functions or modules.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Typical techniques for these are either using stubs/drivers or execution from a debugger environment.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Static testing involves verification, whereas dynamic testing also involves validation.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Passive testing means verifying the system's behavior without any interaction with the software product.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Contrary to active testing, testers do not provide any test data but look at system logs and traces.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] They mine for patterns and specific behavior in order to make some kind of decisions.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] This is related to offline runtime verification and log analysis.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Exploratory testing is an approach to software testing that is concisely described as simultaneous learning, test design and test execution.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Software testing can often be divided into white-box and black-box.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] These two approaches are used to describe the point of view that the tester takes when designing test cases.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] A hybrid approach called grey-box that includes aspects of both boxes may also be applied to software testing methodology.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] White-box testing (also known as clear box testing, glass box testing, transparent box testing, and structural testing) verifies the internal structures or workings of a program, as opposed to the functionality exposed to the end-user.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] In white-box testing, an internal perspective of the system (the source code), as well as programming skills are used to design test cases.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] The tester chooses inputs to exercise paths through the code and determines the appropriate outputs.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] This is analogous to testing nodes in a circuit, e.g., in-circuit testing (ICT).
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] While white-box testing can be applied at the unit, integration, and system levels of the software testing process, it is usually done at the unit level.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] It can test paths within a unit, paths between units during integration, and between subsystems during a system–level test.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Though this method of test design can uncover many errors or problems, it might not detect unimplemented parts of the specification or missing requirements.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Code coverage tools can evaluate the completeness of a test suite that was created with any method, including black-box testing.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] This allows the software team to examine parts of a system that are rarely tested and ensures that the most important function points have been tested.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] 100% statement coverage ensures that all code paths or branches (in terms of control flow) are executed at least once.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] This is helpful in ensuring correct functionality, but not sufficient since the same code may process different inputs correctly or incorrectly.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Black-box testing (also known as functional testing) describes designing test cases without knowledge of the implementation, without reading the source code.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] The testers are only aware of what the software is supposed to do, not how it does it.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Black-box testing methods include: equivalence partitioning, boundary value analysis, all-pairs testing, state transition tables, decision table testing, fuzz testing, model-based testing, use case testing, exploratory testing, and specification-based testing.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Specification-based testing aims to test the functionality of software according to the applicable requirements.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] This level of testing usually requires thorough test cases to be provided to the tester, who then can simply verify that for a given input, the output value (or behavior), either "is" or "is not" the same as the expected value specified in the test case.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Test cases are built around specifications and requirements, i.e., what the application is supposed to do.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] It uses external descriptions of the software, including specifications, requirements, and designs, to derive test cases.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] These tests can be functional or non-functional, though usually functional.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Specification-based testing may be necessary to assure correct functionality, but it is insufficient to guard against complex or high-risk situations.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Black box testing can be used to any level of testing although usually not at the unit level.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Component interface testing is a variation of black-box testing, with the focus on the data values beyond just the related actions of a subsystem component.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] The practice of component interface testing can be used to check the handling of data passed between various units, or subsystem components, beyond full integration testing between those units.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] The data being passed can be considered as "message packets" and the range or data types can be checked for data generated from one unit and tested for validity before being passed into another unit.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] One option for interface testing is to keep a separate log file of data items being passed, often with a timestamp logged to allow analysis of thousands of cases of data passed between units for days or weeks.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Tests can include checking the handling of some extreme data values while other interface variables are passed as normal values.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Unusual data values in an interface can help explain unexpected performance in the next unit.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] The aim of visual testing is to provide developers with the ability to examine what was happening at the point of software failure by presenting the data in such a way that the developer can easily find the information he or she requires, and the information is expressed clearly.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] At the core of visual testing is the idea that showing someone a problem (or a test failure), rather than just describing it, greatly increases clarity and understanding.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Visual testing, therefore, requires the recording of the entire test process – capturing everything that occurs on the test system in video format.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Output videos are supplemented by real-time tester input via picture-in-a-picture webcam and audio commentary from microphones.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Visual testing provides a number of advantages.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] The quality of communication is increased drastically because testers can show the problem (and the events leading up to it) to the developer as opposed to just describing it, and the need to replicate test failures will cease to exist in many cases.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] The developer will have all the evidence he or she requires of a test failure and can instead focus on the cause of the fault and how it should be fixed.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Ad hoc testing and exploratory testing are important methodologies for checking software integrity because they require less preparation time to implement, while the important bugs can be found quickly.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] In ad hoc testing, where testing takes place in an improvised impromptu way, the ability of the tester(s) to base testing off documented methods and then improvise variations of those tests can result in a more rigorous examination of defect fixes.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] However, unless strict documentation of the procedures is maintained, one of the limits of ad hoc testing is lack of repeatability.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Grey-box testing (American spelling: gray-box testing) involves using knowledge of internal data structures and algorithms for purposes of designing tests while executing those tests at the user, or black-box level.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] The tester will often have access to both "the source code and the executable binary." Grey-box testing may also include reverse engineering (using dynamic code analysis) to determine, for instance, boundary values or error messages.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Manipulating input data and formatting output do not qualify as grey-box, as the input and output are clearly outside of the "black box" that we are calling the system under test.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] This distinction is particularly important when conducting integration testing between two modules of code written by two different developers, where only the interfaces are exposed for the test.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] By knowing the underlying concepts of how the software works, the tester makes better-informed testing choices while testing the software from outside.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Typically, a grey-box tester will be permitted to set up an isolated testing environment with activities, such as seeding a database.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] The tester can observe the state of the product being tested after performing certain actions such as executing SQL statements against the database and then executing queries to ensure that the expected changes have been reflected.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Grey-box testing implements intelligent test scenarios based on limited information.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] This will particularly apply to data type handling, exception handling, and so on.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] With the concept of grey-box testing, this "arbitrary distinction" between black- and white-box testing has faded somewhat.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Installation testing is a type of software testing that verifies that users can successfully install and set up software in its intended environments (e.g., operating systems, computer hardware).
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Most software systems have installation procedures that are needed before they can be used for their main purpose.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Installation testing focuses on these procedures and whether they're sufficient for achieving an installed, usable software system.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Procedures of this kind may involve full or partial upgrades, and install/uninstall processes.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] For example, in the case of a lack of backward compatibility, this can occur because the programmers develop and test software only on the latest version of the target environment, which not all users may be running.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] This results in the unintended consequence that the latest work may not function on earlier versions of the target environment, or on older hardware that earlier versions of the target environment were capable of using.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Sometimes such issues can be fixed by proactively abstracting operating system functionality into a separate program module or library.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Sanity testing determines whether it is reasonable to proceed with further testing.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Smoke testing consists of minimal attempts to operate the software, designed to determine whether there are any basic problems that will prevent it from working at all.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Such tests can be used as build verification test.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Regression testing focuses on finding defects after a major code change has occurred.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Specifically, it seeks to uncover software regressions, as degraded or lost features, including old bugs that have come back.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Such regressions occur whenever software functionality that was previously working correctly, stops working as intended.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Typically, regressions occur as an unintended consequence of program changes, when the newly developed part of the software collides with the previously existing code.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Common methods of regression testing include re-running previous sets of test cases and checking whether previously fixed faults have re-emerged.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] The depth of testing depends on the phase in the release process and the risk of the added features.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] They can either be complete, for changes added late in the release or deemed to be risky, or be very shallow, consisting of positive tests on each feature, if the changes are early in the release or deemed to be of low risk.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Acceptance testing is system-level testing to ensure the software meets customer expectations.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Acceptance testing may be performed at the end or in the middle of a project, including after each completed user story in an agile project.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Tests are frequently grouped into these levels by where they are performed in the software development process, or by the level of specificity of the test.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Sometimes, UAT is performed by the customer, in their environment and on their own hardware.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] OAT is used to conduct operational readiness (prerelease) of a product, service or system as part of a quality management system.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] OAT is a common type of non-functional software testing, used mainly in software development and software maintenance projects.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] This type of testing focuses on the operational readiness of the system to be supported, or to become part of the production environment.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Hence, it is also known as operational readiness testing (ORT) or operations readiness and assurance (OR&A) testing.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Functional testing within OAT is limited to those tests that are required to verify the *non-functional* aspects of the system.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] In addition, the software testing should ensure that the portability of the system, as well as working as expected, does not also damage or partially corrupt its operating environment or cause other processes within that environment to become inoperative.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Contractual acceptance testing is performed based on the contract's acceptance criteria defined during the agreement of the contract, while regulatory acceptance testing is performed based on the relevant regulations to the software product.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Both of these two tests can be performed by users or independent testers.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Regulation acceptance testing sometimes involves the regulatory agencies auditing the test results.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Alpha testing is simulated or actual operational testing by potential users/customers or an independent test team at the developers' site.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Alpha testing is often employed for off-the-shelf software as a form of internal acceptance testing before the software goes to beta testing.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Beta testing comes after alpha testing and can be considered a form of external user acceptance testing.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Versions of the software, known as beta versions, are released to a limited audience outside of the programming team known as beta testers.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] The software is released to groups of people so that further testing can ensure the product has few faults or bugs.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Beta versions can be made available to the open public to increase the feedback field to a maximal number of future users and to deliver value earlier, for an extended or even indefinite period of time (perpetual beta).
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Functional testing refers to activities that verify a specific action or function of the code.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] These are usually found in the code requirements documentation, although some development methodologies work from use cases or user stories.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Non-functional testing refers to aspects of the software that may not be related to a specific function or user action, such as scalability or other performance, behavior under certain constraints, or security.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Testing will determine the breaking point, the point at which extremes of scalability or performance leads to unstable execution.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Non-functional requirements tend to be those that reflect the quality of the product, particularly in the context of the suitability perspective of its users.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Continuous testing is the process of executing automated tests as part of the software delivery pipeline to obtain immediate feedback on the business risks associated with a software release candidate.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Continuous testing includes the validation of both functional requirements and non-functional requirements; the scope of testing extends from validating bottom-up requirements or user stories to assessing the system requirements associated with overarching business goals.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Destructive testing attempts to cause the software or a sub-system to fail.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] It verifies whether the software functions properly when it receives invalid or unexpected inputs, thereby assessing the robustness of input validation and error-management routines.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Software fault injection, in the form of fuzzing, is an example of failure testing.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Various commercial non-functional testing tools are linked from the software fault injection page; there are also numerous open-source and free software tools available that perform destructive testing.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Performance testing is generally executed to determine how a system or sub-system performs in terms of responsiveness and stability under a particular workload.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] It can also serve to investigate, measure, validate or verify other quality attributes of the system, such as scalability, reliability and resource usage.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] There is little agreement on what the specific goals of performance testing are.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] The terms load testing, performance testing, scalability testing, and volume testing, are often used interchangeably.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Real-time software systems have strict timing constraints.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] To test if timing constraints are met, real-time testing is used.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Usability testing is to check if the user interface is easy to use and understand.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] It is concerned mainly with the use of the application.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] This is not a kind of testing that can be automated; actual human users are needed, being monitored by skilled UI designers.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Usability testing can use structured models to check how well an interface works.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] The Stanton, Theofanos, and Joshi (2015) model looks at user experience, and the Al-Sharafat and Qadoumi (2016) model is for expert evaluation, helping to assess usability in digital applications.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Accessibility testing is done to ensure that the software is accessible to persons with disabilities.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Security testing is essential for software that processes confidential data to prevent system intrusion by hackers.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Testing for internationalization and localization validates that the software can be used with different languages and geographic regions.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] The process of pseudolocalization is used to test the ability of an application to be translated to another language, and make it easier to identify when the localization process may introduce new bugs into the product.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Globalization testing verifies that the software is adapted for a new culture, such as different currencies or time zones.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Actual translation to human languages must be tested, too.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Development testing is a software development process that involves the synchronized application of a broad spectrum of defect prevention and detection strategies in order to reduce software development risks, time, and costs.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] It is performed by the software developer or engineer during the construction phase of the software development lifecycle.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Development testing aims to eliminate construction errors before code is promoted to other testing; this strategy is intended to increase the quality of the resulting software as well as the efficiency of the overall development process.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Depending on the organization's expectations for software development, development testing might include static code analysis, data flow analysis, metrics analysis, peer code reviews, unit testing, code coverage analysis, traceability, and other software testing practices.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] A/B testing is a method of running a controlled experiment to determine if a proposed change is more effective than the current approach.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Customers are routed to either a current version (control) of a feature, or to a modified version (treatment) and data is collected to determine which version is better at achieving the desired outcome.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Concurrent or concurrency testing assesses the behaviour and performance of software and systems that use concurrent computing, generally under normal usage conditions.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Typical problems this type of testing will expose are deadlocks, race conditions and problems with shared memory/resource handling.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] In software testing, conformance testing verifies that a product performs according to its specified standards.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Compilers, for instance, are extensively tested to determine whether they meet the recognized standard for that language.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] For example, every output from a serialization function should be accepted by the corresponding deserialization function, and every output from a sort function should be a monotonically increasing list containing exactly the same elements as its input.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Property testing libraries allow the user to control the strategy by which random inputs are constructed, to ensure coverage of degenerate cases, or inputs featuring specific patterns that are needed to fully exercise aspects of the implementation under test.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Property testing is also sometimes known as "generative testing" or "QuickCheck testing" since it was introduced and popularized by the Haskell library QuickCheck.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Metamorphic testing (MT) is a property-based software testing technique, which can be an effective approach for addressing the test oracle problem and test case generation problem.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] The test oracle problem is the difficulty of determining the expected outcomes of selected test cases or to determine whether the actual outputs agree with the expected outcomes.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] VCR testing, also known as "playback testing" or "record/replay" testing, is a testing technique for increasing the reliability and speed of regression tests that involve a component that is slow or unreliable to communicate with, often a third-party API outside of the tester's control.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] It involves making a recording ("cassette") of the system's interactions with the external component, and then replaying the recorded interactions as a substitute for communicating with the external system on subsequent runs of the test.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] The technique was popularized in web development by the Ruby library vcr.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] It is often used in the context of distributed systems, service-oriented software architectures, and microservices.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Since the early 2020s, artificial intelligence has increasingly been integrated into software testing workflows.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] AI-driven testing methods automate the creation of test cases, dynamically adapt to changes, and leverage machine learning to identify high-risk areas of the codebase — an approach that enhances regression testing efficiency while expanding overall test coverage.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] A key development is **self-healing test automation**, in which automated tests automatically detect and adapt to changes in a user interface without human intervention.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Studies of AI-driven test automation across over 3,600 grey literature sources identified self-healing test scripts as one of the most common AI solutions in practice.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] A case study presented at the 2023 International Conference on Information Management and Technology (ICIMTech) found that integrating shift-left testing into an agile development methodology over one year measurably reduced the number of bugs reaching production.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] In an organization, testers may be in a separate team from the rest of the software development team or they may be integrated into one team.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Software testing can also be performed by non-dedicated software testers.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] In the 1980s, the term *software tester* started to be used to denote a separate profession.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Notable software testing roles and titles include: *test manager*, *test lead*, *test analyst*, *test designer*, *tester*, *automation developer*, and *test administrator*.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Organizations that develop software, perform testing differently, but there are common patterns.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] In waterfall development, testing is generally performed after the code is completed, but before the product is shipped to the customer.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] This practice often results in the testing phase being used as a project buffer to compensate for project delays, thereby compromising the time devoted to testing.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Some contend that the waterfall process allows for testing to start when the development project starts and to be a continuous process until the project finishes.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Agile software development commonly involves testing while the code is being written and organizing teams with both programmers and testers and with team members performing both programming and testing.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] One agile practice, test-driven software development (TDD), is a way of unit testing such that unit-level testing is performed while writing the product code.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Test code is updated as new features are added and failure conditions are discovered (bugs fixed).
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Commonly, the unit test code is maintained with the project code, integrated in the build process, and run on each build and as part of regression testing.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Goals of this continuous integration is to support development and reduce defects.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] Even in organizations that separate teams by programming and testing functions, many often have the programmers perform unit testing.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] The sample below is common for waterfall development.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p01] The same activities are commonly found in other development models, but might be described differently.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] The terms verification and validation are commonly used interchangeably in the industry; it is also common to see these two terms defined with contradictory definitions.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] Verification is the process of evaluating a system or component to determine whether the products of a given development phase satisfy the conditions imposed at the start of that phase.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] Validation is the process of evaluating a system or component during or at the end of the development process to determine whether it satisfies specified requirements.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] Verification is confirmation by examination and through provision of objective evidence that specified requirements have been fulfilled.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] Validation is confirmation by examination and through provision of objective evidence that the requirements for a specific intended use or application have been fulfilled.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] The contradiction is caused by the use of the concepts of requirements and specified requirements but with different meanings.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] In the case of IEEE standards, the specified requirements, mentioned in the definition of validation, are the set of problems, needs and wants of the stakeholders that the software must solve and satisfy.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] Such requirements are documented in a Software Requirements Specification (SRS).
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] And, the products mentioned in the definition of verification, are the output artifacts of every phase of the software development process.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] These products are, in fact, specifications such as Architectural Design Specification, Detailed Design Specification, etc.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] The SRS is also a specification, but it cannot be verified (at least not in the sense used here – more on this subject below).
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] But, for the ISO 9000, the specified requirements are the set of specifications, as just mentioned above, that must be verified.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] A specification, as previously explained, is the product of a software development process phase that receives another specification as input.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] A specification is verified successfully when it correctly implements its input specification.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] All the specifications can be verified except the SRS because it is the first one (it can be validated, though).
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] An example scenario be that the Design Specification must implement the SRS, and the Construction phase artifacts must implement the Design Specification.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] So, when these words are defined in common terms, the apparent contradiction disappears.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] Both the SRS and the software must be validated.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] The SRS can be validated statically by consulting with the stakeholders.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] Nevertheless, running some partial implementation of the software or a prototype of any kind (dynamic testing) and obtaining positive feedback from them, can further increase the certainty that the SRS is correctly formulated.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] On the other hand, the software, as a final and running product (not its artifacts and documents, including the source code) must be validated dynamically with the stakeholders by executing the software and having them to try it.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] Some might argue that, for SRS, the input is the words of stakeholders and, therefore, SRS validation is the same as SRS verification.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] Thinking this way is not advisable as it only causes more confusion.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] It is better to think of verification as a process involving a formal and technical input document.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] In some organizations, software testing is part of a software quality assurance (SQA) process.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] In SQA, software process specialists and auditors are concerned with the software development process rather than just the artifacts such as documentation, code and systems.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] They examine and change the software engineering process itself to reduce the number of faults that end up in the delivered software: the so-called defect rate.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] What constitutes an acceptable defect rate depends on the nature of the software; a flight simulator video game would have much higher defect tolerance than software for an actual airplane.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] Although there are close links with SQA, testing departments often exist independently, and there may be no SQA function in some companies.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] Software testing is an activity to investigate software under test in order to provide quality-related information to stakeholders.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] By contrast, QA (quality assurance) is the implementation of policies and procedures intended to prevent defects from reaching customers.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] Quality measures include such topics as correctness, completeness, security and ISO/IEC 9126 requirements such as capability, reliability, efficiency, portability, maintainability, compatibility, and usability.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] There are a number of frequently used software metrics, or measures, which are used to assist in determining the state of the software or the adequacy of the testing.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] A software testing process can produce several artifacts.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] The actual artifacts produced are a factor of the software development model used, stakeholder and organisational needs.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] A test plan is a document detailing the approach that will be taken for intended test activities.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] The plan may include aspects such as objectives, scope, processes and procedures, personnel requirements, and contingency plans.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] The test plan could come in the form of a single plan that includes all test types (like an acceptance or system test plan) and planning considerations, or it may be issued as a master test plan that provides an overview of more than one detailed test plan (a plan of a plan).
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] A test plan can be, in some cases, part of a wide "test strategy" which documents overall testing approaches, which may itself be a master test plan or even a separate artifact.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] In software development, a traceability matrix (TM) is a document, usually in the form of a table, used to assist in determining the completeness of a relationship by correlating any two baselined documents using a many-to-many relationship comparison.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] It is often used with high-level requirements (these often consist of marketing requirements) and detailed requirements of the product to the matching parts of high-level design, detailed design, test plan, and test cases.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] A test case normally consists of a unique identifier, requirement references from a design specification, preconditions, events, a series of steps (also known as actions) to follow, input, output, expected result, and the actual result.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] Clinically defined, a test case is an input and an expected result.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] This can be as terse as "for condition x your derived result is y", although normally test cases describe in more detail the input scenario and what results might be expected.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] It can occasionally be a series of steps (but often steps are contained in a separate test procedure that can be exercised against multiple test cases, as a matter of economy) but with one expected result or expected outcome.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] The optional fields are a test case ID, test step, or order of execution number, related requirement(s), depth, test category, author, and check boxes for whether the test is automatable and has been automated.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] Larger test cases may also contain prerequisite states or steps, and descriptions.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] A test case should also contain a place for the actual result.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] These steps can be stored in a word processor document, spreadsheet, database, or other common repositories.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] In a database system, you may also be able to see past test results, who generated the results, and what system configuration was used to generate those results.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] These past results would usually be stored in a separate table.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] A test script is a procedure or programming code that replicates user actions.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] Initially, the term was derived from the product of work created by automated regression test tools.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] A test case will be a baseline to create test scripts using a tool or a program.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] In software development, a test suite, less commonly known as a validation suite, is a collection of test cases that are intended to be used to test a software program to show that it has some specified set of behaviors.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] A test suite often contains detailed instructions or goals for each collection of test cases and information on the system configuration to be used during testing.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] A group of test cases may also contain prerequisite states or steps and descriptions of the following tests.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] In most cases, multiple sets of values or data are used to test the same functionality of a particular feature.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] All the test values and changeable environmental components are collected in separate files and stored as test data.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] It is also useful to provide this data to the client and with the product or a project.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] There are techniques to generate Test data.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] The software, tools, samples of data input and output, and configurations are all referred to collectively as a test harness.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] A test run is a collection of test cases or test suites that the user is executing and comparing the expected with the actual results.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] Once complete, a report or all executed tests may be generated.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] Several certification programs exist to support the professional aspirations of software testers and quality assurance specialists.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] A few practitioners argue that the testing field is not ready for certification, as mentioned in the controversy section.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] is so expensive relative to its value that it should be used sparingly.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] The test automation then can be considered as a way to capture and implement the requirements.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] As a general rule, the larger the system and the greater the complexity, the greater the ROI in test automation.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] Also, the investment in tools and expertise can be amortized over multiple projects with the right level of knowledge sharing within an organization.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] Significant opposition has formed out of the ranks of the context-driven school of software testing about the ISO 29119 standard.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] Professional testing associations, such as the International Society for Software Testing, have attempted to have the standard withdrawn.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] No certification now offered actually requires the applicant to show their ability to test software.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] No certification is based on a widely accepted body of knowledge.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] Certification itself cannot measure an individual's productivity, their skill, or practical knowledge, and cannot guarantee their competence, or professionalism as a tester.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/software-testing-p02] There are opposing views on the applicability of studies used to show the relative expense of fixing defects depending on their introduction and detection.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] A **test fixture** is a device used to consistently test some item, device, or piece of software.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] Test fixtures are used in the testing of electronics, software and physical devices.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] In testing electronic equipment such as circuit boards, electronic components, and chips, a test fixture is a device or setup designed to hold the device under test in place and allow it to be tested by being subjected to controlled electronic test signals.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] Examples are a bed of nails tester or smart fixture.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] Test fixtures can come in different shapes, sizes, and functions.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] There are several different types of test fixtures, including In-Circuit Test Fixtures, Functional Test Fixtures, and Wireless Test Fixtures.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] In Circuit Test (ICT) fixtures individually test each component on a PCB, while functional test fixtures assess the entire board's functionality.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] Functional test fixtures simulate real-world conditions, whereas ICT is more focused on detecting assembly defects like short circuits or missing components.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] An In-Circuit Test fixture can come in both Inline and Standard variations.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] An Inline Test Fixture is designed for fast, automated testing directly within a production line, ideal for high-volume manufacturing where continuous testing maximises efficiency.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] A Standard Test Fixture, on the other hand, usually requires manual loading, making it well-suited to smaller-scale or specialised testing.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] In the context of software, a test fixture (also called "test context") is used to set up the system state and input data needed for test execution.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] For example, the Ruby on Rails web framework uses YAML to initialize a database with known parameters before running a test.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] This allows for tests to be repeatable, which is one of the key features of an effective test framework.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] In most cases, a custom test fixture will normally require custom test software.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] This software is created in order to ensure optimal testing performance and seamless integration.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] The custom software can be configured to carry out a number of different tests from BIST (Built-In Self Test) to advanced JTAG Implementation.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] Test fixtures can be set up three different ways: in-line, delegate, and implicit.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] Delegate setup places the test fixture in a separate standalone helper method that is accessed by multiple test methods.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] Implicit setup places the test fixture in a setup method which is used to set up multiple test methods.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] This differs from delegate setup in that the overall setup of multiple tests is in a single setup method where the test fixture gets created rather than each test method having its own setup procedures and linking to an external test fixture.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] The main advantage of a test fixture is that it allows for tests to be repeatable since each test is always starting with the same setup.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] Test fixtures also ease test code design by allowing the developer to separate methods into different functions and reuse each function for other tests.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] Further, test fixtures preconfigure tests into a known initial state instead of working with whatever was left from a previous test run.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] A disadvantage is that it could lead to duplication of test fixtures if using in-line setup.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] It is considered bad practice when implicit test fixtures are too general, or when a test method sets up a test fixture and does not use it during the test.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] A more subtle issue is if the test methods ignore certain fields within the test fixture.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] Another bad practice is a test setup that contains more steps than needed for the test; this is a problem seen in in-line setup.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] A test case is considered "unsafe" when it modifies its fixture(s).
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] An unsafe test case can render subsequent tests useless by leaving the fixture in an unexpected state.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] It also causes the order of tests to be important: a modified fixture must be reset if more tests are to be run after an unsafe test.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] Examples of fixtures include loading a database with a specific known set of data, erasing a hard disk and installing a known clean operating system installation, copying a specific known set of files, or the preparation of input data as well as set-up and creation of mock objects.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] Software which is used to run reproducible tests systematically on a piece of software under test is known as a test harness; part of its job is to set up suitable test fixtures.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] In generic xUnit, a *test fixture* is all the things that must be in place in order to run a test and expect a particular outcome.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] Frequently fixtures are created by handling *setUp()* and *tearDown()* events of the unit testing framework.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] In *setUp()* one would create the expected state for the test and in *tearDown()* it would clean up what had been set up.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] In physical testing, a fixture is a device or apparatus to hold or support the test specimen during the test.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] The influence of test fixtures on test results is important and is an ongoing subject of research.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] Many test methods detail the requirements of test fixtures in the text of the document.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] Some fixtures employ clamps, wedge grips and pincer grips.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] Further types of construction include eccentric roller fixtures, thread grips and button head grips and rope grips.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] Mechanical holding apparatuses provide the clamping force via arms, wedges or eccentric wheel to the jaws.
[src:googletest-cpp-lib/test-fixture] Additionally there are pneumatic and hydraulic fixtures for tensile testing that allow very fast clamping procedures and very high clamping forces.
